WEBVTT

00:02.836 --> 00:03.926
<i>CLAIRE:
Previously...</i>

00:04.004 --> 00:05.334
You’re to be congratulated.

00:05.422 --> 00:10.632
Your son is now the proud owner
of River Run.

00:10.719 --> 00:12.099
I can procure you
whatever you wish.

00:12.179 --> 00:13.809
I know an Irish
seafaring gentlemen

00:13.889 --> 00:15.479
who does business
in Wilmington.

00:15.557 --> 00:17.357
My husband’s whiskey venture...

00:17.476 --> 00:20.316
Mr. Bonnet doesn’t do business
with people he doesn’t know.

00:20.395 --> 00:23.605
Mr. Bonnet will be
personally meeting
Mr. Alexander Malcolm.

00:23.690 --> 00:25.150
You must kill Stephen Bonnet.

00:25.234 --> 00:26.944
I don’t know if I can take
another man’s life.

00:27.027 --> 00:28.867
A plan has been put in motion

00:28.987 --> 00:30.537
to find
and kill Stephen Bonnet.

00:30.614 --> 00:33.034
Bonnet could have the right
to take Jemmy away from us.

00:33.116 --> 00:34.286
He attacked me.

00:34.368 --> 00:35.788
Well, people of this time see

00:35.869 --> 00:37.959
the child as proof that you
were a willing participant.

00:38.038 --> 00:39.708
<i>BRIANNA:
I could have been brave.
</i> <i>I could have fought.</i>

00:39.831 --> 00:41.371
<i>I hate myself
for what happened.</i>

00:41.500 --> 00:43.720
‐ You couldn’t have stopped it.
‐ I could have tried harder.

00:43.835 --> 00:45.005
It took courage not to fight.

00:45.087 --> 00:46.717
If ye did,
he would have killed ye.

00:48.549 --> 00:50.559
<i>CHOIR:
♪ Sing me a song ♪</i>

00:50.676 --> 00:53.556
<i>♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪</i>

00:53.637 --> 00:56.057
<i>♪ Say, could that lass ♪</i>

00:56.139 --> 00:59.149
<i>♪ Be I? ♪</i>

00:59.226 --> 01:01.396
<i>♪ Merry of soul ♪</i>

01:01.478 --> 01:04.398
<i>♪ She sailed on a day ♪</i>

01:04.481 --> 01:06.481
<i>♪ Over the sea ♪</i>

01:06.567 --> 01:09.527
<i>♪ To Skye ♪</i>

01:09.611 --> 01:12.361
<i>♪ Billow and breeze ♪</i>

01:12.447 --> 01:14.747
<i>♪ Islands and seas ♪</i>

01:14.866 --> 01:17.826
<i>♪ Mountains of rain and sun ♪</i>

01:17.911 --> 01:20.281
<i>♪ Mountains of rain
</i> <i>and sun ♪</i>

01:20.414 --> 01:22.584
<i>♪ All that was good ♪</i>

01:22.708 --> 01:24.708
<i>♪ All that was fair ♪</i>

01:24.793 --> 01:27.293
<i>♪ All that was me ♪</i>

01:27.421 --> 01:30.421
<i>♪ Is gone ♪</i>

01:30.549 --> 01:32.679
<i>♪ Sing me a song ♪</i>

01:32.759 --> 01:35.559
<i>♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪</i>

01:35.637 --> 01:37.597
<i>♪ Say, could that lass ♪</i>

01:37.681 --> 01:40.641
<i>♪ Be I? ♪</i>

01:40.767 --> 01:43.267
<i>♪ Merry of soul ♪</i>

01:43.395 --> 01:45.815
<i>♪ She sailed on a day ♪</i>

01:45.939 --> 01:50.699
<i>♪ Over the sea ♪</i>

01:50.777 --> 01:56.697
<i>♪ To Skye ♪</i>

01:56.783 --> 01:59.613
[ dramatic music ]

01:59.703 --> 02:02.123
<i>♪</i>

02:02.205 --> 02:06.295
<i>WOMAN:
♪ Sing me a song ♪</i>

02:06.418 --> 02:08.548
<i>♪ Of a lass ♪</i>

02:08.629 --> 02:11.639
<i>♪ That is gone ♪</i>

02:11.715 --> 02:16.175
<i>♪ Say, could that lass ♪</i>

02:16.303 --> 02:20.093
<i>♪ Be I? ♪</i>

02:24.603 --> 02:26.853
<i>FORBES:
</i> <i>The time has come
to approach the magistrate</i>

02:26.980 --> 02:29.600
with our request.

02:29.691 --> 02:34.111
Obviously, your occupation...

02:34.196 --> 02:36.656
makes matters
a‐a‐a bit more difficult.

02:36.782 --> 02:38.822
A gentleman has no occupation.

02:38.950 --> 02:42.280
Precisely, and that is why,
as your lawyer,

02:42.371 --> 02:45.121
I advise you to be more
discreet with your dealings.

02:45.207 --> 02:47.587
<i>You have allies among
</i> <i>the wealthy.</i>

02:47.668 --> 02:50.678
You’ve been exonerated
for your crimes.

02:50.754 --> 02:53.084
But for now,
I recommend that you lie low.

02:53.173 --> 02:56.253
I’d like to lay low
under my regular mare there.

02:56.343 --> 02:58.173
[ women laughing ]

02:58.261 --> 03:00.551
People might turn
a‐a blind eye

03:00.681 --> 03:03.341
to smuggling tobacco
or whiskey,

03:03.433 --> 03:06.643
but there have been rumblings
that you’re trading commodities

03:06.728 --> 03:08.028
of a female nature.

03:08.105 --> 03:10.855
My business is none
of their business.

03:10.941 --> 03:13.401
Do you want custody of your son
or not, Mr. Bonnet?

03:13.527 --> 03:16.447
I’ve made allies due to those
very dealings, Mr. Forbes.

03:16.530 --> 03:19.370
They owe their wealth
and influence in part to me,

03:19.491 --> 03:21.361
as do you.

03:21.451 --> 03:24.741
So I suggest you start
to behave more as my lawyer

03:24.871 --> 03:25.951
and less as my priest.

03:26.039 --> 03:27.839
Oh, you have a priest?

03:27.916 --> 03:30.416
[ indistinct chatter ]

03:30.544 --> 03:33.834
I need you to consult
with the magistrate.

03:33.922 --> 03:35.792
When will we have
his signature, sir?

03:35.882 --> 03:38.252
I’ve provided him
with the names of the witnesses

03:38.385 --> 03:39.885
from the tavern,

03:40.011 --> 03:41.551
and I’ve confirmed
that they will attest

03:41.680 --> 03:43.600
to the circumstances
on said evening.

03:43.724 --> 03:47.184
<i>We should have a signature
by the end of the week,</i>

03:47.269 --> 03:50.989
and young Jeremiah will be
with his father.

03:51.064 --> 03:52.774
Huh.

03:52.899 --> 03:55.239
From your lips to God’s ears,
Mr. Forbes.

03:58.905 --> 04:01.535
[ dramatic music ]

04:01.616 --> 04:03.286
<i>♪</i>

04:03.410 --> 04:06.250
If we might discuss
the matter of my compensation.

04:06.371 --> 04:08.331
<i>♪</i>

04:08.415 --> 04:10.665
I’m no fortune teller...

04:10.751 --> 04:13.831
but once I claim my son,
I foresee an unlucky accident

04:13.920 --> 04:16.540
for Jocasta Innes
and her new bridegroom.

04:16.631 --> 04:20.091
Such a shame, them being
married for so short a time.

04:20.177 --> 04:24.227
How she chose that
old buffoon I’ll never know.

04:24.306 --> 04:27.606
And she humiliated me
during my courtship
with her niece.

04:27.726 --> 04:30.526
When River Run’s mine...

04:30.604 --> 04:32.314
you’ll get your money.

04:32.439 --> 04:35.359
The agreed upon 20%.

04:35.442 --> 04:37.442
We’ll have a dram
on the front porch

04:37.569 --> 04:38.779
in celebration.

04:38.862 --> 04:39.942
I look forward to it.

04:40.071 --> 04:41.611
[ ominous music ]

04:41.698 --> 04:43.578
In the meantime,

04:43.658 --> 04:46.038
Mistress Innes has asked
to see me.

04:46.119 --> 04:48.129
I’m intending to sail up
on the <i>Sally Ann</i>

04:48.205 --> 04:49.835
to Cross Creek tomorrow.

04:49.956 --> 04:52.506
<i>♪</i>

04:52.626 --> 04:54.836
Not a word of this to anyone.

04:54.961 --> 04:57.831
Confidentiality is
my livelihood.

04:57.964 --> 05:00.004
<i>♪</i>

05:00.133 --> 05:01.173
[ glasses clink ]

05:01.301 --> 05:03.971
<i>♪</i>

05:12.646 --> 05:14.526
I have a really bad feeling
about this.

05:17.150 --> 05:20.270
I want Bonnet out of our lives
for good...

05:20.362 --> 05:23.572
and nowhere near you
or our son.

05:23.657 --> 05:26.077
Getting rid of Bonnet
is for the greater good.

05:26.159 --> 05:27.329
Yes.

05:29.037 --> 05:32.497
Though I still don’t trust
Philip Wylie...

05:32.582 --> 05:35.662
even though he stands to make
a lot of money from this deal.

05:35.794 --> 05:37.464
I think he’ll keep his word.

05:37.546 --> 05:38.886
But what if he doesn’t?

05:39.005 --> 05:40.845
Well, if he doesn’t,
I’ll likely be dead.

05:40.966 --> 05:43.056
So if ye could find the time,

05:43.176 --> 05:45.846
I’ll appreciate it
if ye’ll make him
suffer for it.

05:45.971 --> 05:50.181
[ door creaks opens, closes ]

05:50.308 --> 05:54.438
JAMIE:
Ah, here comes
our go‐between now...

05:54.521 --> 05:56.311
Mr. Alexander Malcolm.

05:57.983 --> 05:59.353
Glad you could join us.

06:03.029 --> 06:04.949
Well, Uncle, is this
what ye had in mind?

06:05.031 --> 06:06.691
Even better.

06:08.368 --> 06:09.748
What about my markings?

06:09.870 --> 06:12.170
CLAIRE:
I’ll help you find some clay
to cover them up.

06:12.247 --> 06:15.207
Though we don’t have to fool
them for very long.

06:15.333 --> 06:16.953
We must get to Wylie’s Landing
before the parley.

06:17.043 --> 06:19.083
We’ll leave at dawn.

06:19.212 --> 06:21.462
If we’ve no’ return
to Wilmington in two days,

06:21.548 --> 06:23.218
go back to the Ridge.

06:23.300 --> 06:25.850
If you don’t return,
we’re coming to find you.

06:25.927 --> 06:27.477
I thought ye might say that.

06:28.805 --> 06:30.975
Dinna fash.

06:31.057 --> 06:32.397
Bonnet’s only a man.

06:33.727 --> 06:34.897
And nothing more.

06:34.978 --> 06:37.818
[ solemn music ]

06:37.898 --> 06:39.778
<i>♪</i>

06:39.900 --> 06:42.030
MAN:
It is rather small, isn’t it?

06:42.110 --> 06:43.860
Well, sometimes
the smallest things in life

06:43.945 --> 06:44.985
are the most useful.

06:45.071 --> 06:46.531
What use do you have for it?

06:46.615 --> 06:49.075
Well, it will be an instrument,
uh, for a physician.

06:49.159 --> 06:51.119
It will hold medicinal liquid.

06:51.244 --> 06:53.164
[ scoffs ]
But it has a hole
on both sides.

06:53.246 --> 06:54.996
It’s not finished yet.

06:55.081 --> 06:56.991
The smith is going to make
something for the bottom

06:57.083 --> 06:58.913
and a needle to put in the top.

06:59.044 --> 07:00.544
It’s a syringe.

07:00.629 --> 07:02.389
Ah, I’ve heard of those,

07:02.464 --> 07:05.214
usually a tube fitted
with a piston.

07:05.300 --> 07:07.140
Aren’t syringes made of brass?

07:07.260 --> 07:09.510
Well, usually, yes.

07:09.596 --> 07:11.636
But I prefer
when they’re made of glass.

07:11.765 --> 07:13.555
It’s easier
to sterilize‐‐

07:13.642 --> 07:15.722
clean...

07:15.810 --> 07:18.520
to use before you heal.

07:18.605 --> 07:22.855
Well, I did blow a glass tube
for a thermometer last spring.

07:22.943 --> 07:25.823
I suppose a glass tube
is a glass tube.

07:25.946 --> 07:27.236
Come back again
in a few days’ time.

07:27.322 --> 07:28.732
I’ll see what I can do.

07:28.823 --> 07:31.113
CLAIRE:
Thank you.

07:31.242 --> 07:33.782
[ sighs ]
Well, that’s one down.

07:33.870 --> 07:35.450
Let’s hope
the smith doesn’t think

07:35.538 --> 07:37.628
we’re practicing witchcraft
asking for a hollow needle.

07:37.749 --> 07:39.419
[ chuckles ]
No kidding.

07:39.501 --> 07:41.501
When was the hypodermic needle
invented, again?

07:41.628 --> 07:43.218
Not for a while yet.

07:43.296 --> 07:45.676
I really need one.

07:45.799 --> 07:47.719
You’ve seen your father.

07:47.801 --> 07:49.921
He has a knack for almost
getting himself killed

07:50.011 --> 07:51.761
every time he gets out of bed.

07:51.846 --> 07:56.516
I swear that man is like a cat.
Got nine lives, if not more.

07:56.643 --> 07:58.933
[ both chuckle ]

07:59.020 --> 08:01.890
[ dramatic music ]

08:01.982 --> 08:04.852
<i>♪</i>

08:39.019 --> 08:40.529
[ sighs ]

08:43.148 --> 08:44.608
What if he doesn’t come alone?

08:44.691 --> 08:46.231
I’m sure he won’t.

08:46.359 --> 08:48.619
He’ll bring his sailors
wi’ him.

08:50.697 --> 08:52.697
What do ye ken about them
from yer voyage?

08:55.410 --> 08:58.710
They sail with him
like they eat scorpion fish,

08:58.788 --> 09:01.548
<i>only when they’re hungry
and have no other options.</i>

09:01.624 --> 09:05.874
His sailors follow his commands
out of fear, not love.

09:05.962 --> 09:08.922
So long as we take care
not to give them reason
to think we’re a threat,

09:09.049 --> 09:10.259
I don’t think they’ll be
much trouble

09:10.383 --> 09:11.753
about Bonnet’s fate.

09:11.885 --> 09:14.725
Hmm. Except they’ll be in need
of new employment.

09:16.139 --> 09:18.059
Keep yer wits about ye.

09:18.141 --> 09:19.351
This is our one chance.

09:20.810 --> 09:21.850
There may not be another.

09:23.646 --> 09:25.396
BRIANNA:
So we’ve got the kelp
for the iodine.

09:25.482 --> 09:26.982
And what else
are we looking for?

09:27.067 --> 09:28.657
CLAIRE:
Well, certain shells‐‐

09:28.735 --> 09:31.235
I can grind them down
to use their calcium‐‐

09:31.362 --> 09:33.692
and maybe some sponges
to use in surgery.

09:33.782 --> 09:34.942
I can do shells.

09:35.075 --> 09:36.745
‐ I’ll save some for Jem.
‐ Hmm.

09:36.826 --> 09:39.666
Maybe I’ll make him a mobile,
might make him sleep better.

09:39.746 --> 09:42.586
[ foreboding music ]

09:42.707 --> 09:45.587
<i>♪</i>

09:53.426 --> 09:55.596
When he comes, I want to be
the one to kill him.

09:55.720 --> 09:58.680
<i>♪</i>

09:58.765 --> 10:00.015
Now ye’re telling me.

10:00.100 --> 10:02.320
You said it yourself‐‐
he’s just a man.

10:02.435 --> 10:03.515
I ken what I said.

10:03.603 --> 10:05.103
I know what you’re thinking.

10:05.230 --> 10:07.950
I’ve never killed a man
or fought in battle.

10:08.066 --> 10:11.316
<i>I’m no marksman and only
a half‐decent swordsman,</i>

10:11.444 --> 10:12.824
but he’s mine.

10:14.114 --> 10:15.194
I will take him.

10:15.281 --> 10:17.401
[ dramatic music ]

10:17.492 --> 10:19.782
Brianna’s yer daughter,
but she’s my wife.

10:19.869 --> 10:22.789
<i>♪</i>

10:28.628 --> 10:30.218
So...

10:30.296 --> 10:32.636
don’t hesitate.

10:32.757 --> 10:35.637
Dinna challenge him.
Kill him the moment
you have the chance.

10:35.760 --> 10:37.720
<i>♪</i>

10:37.804 --> 10:40.804
If you fall, Roger Mac,
know I will avenge ye.

10:42.559 --> 10:44.479
And if you fall,
I will avenge you.

10:44.561 --> 10:46.971
<i>♪</i>

10:47.063 --> 10:48.643
A bargain, is it?

10:48.773 --> 10:51.403
<i>♪</i>

10:51.484 --> 10:53.654
A rare bargain indeed.

10:53.778 --> 10:56.698
<i>♪</i>

11:04.330 --> 11:07.660
‐ [ Brianna squeals ]
‐ [ both laugh ]

11:07.750 --> 11:10.000
‐ [ Claire sighs ]
‐ BRIANNA: Wait.
Is that what I think it is?

11:10.086 --> 11:11.086
[ ethereal music ]

11:11.171 --> 11:13.001
<i>Wow.</i>

11:13.089 --> 11:14.679
[ sighs ]

11:14.799 --> 11:18.179
We didn’t often get to see
sights like that in our time.

11:18.261 --> 11:20.341
<i>♪</i>

11:20.430 --> 11:23.060
There’s so much here
that’s unspoiled.

11:23.183 --> 11:24.683
There’s so many of them now.

11:24.809 --> 11:27.479
And to think by the end
of the 19th century,

11:27.562 --> 11:30.772
whalers had all
but wiped them out.

11:30.857 --> 11:34.777
I can see why Melville was
inspired to write about them.

11:34.861 --> 11:37.981
‐ God, I love <i>Moby Dick.
</i> ‐ Yeah, me too.

11:38.072 --> 11:41.742
I remember seeing a whale fluke
off of Cape Cod once.

11:42.911 --> 11:45.621
Remember when we used to race
there on the beach
when I was little?

11:45.705 --> 11:46.705
[ giggles ]

11:46.831 --> 11:49.621
<i>♪</i>

11:49.709 --> 11:51.759
[ chuckles ]

11:51.878 --> 11:53.968
[ both laughing ]

11:54.047 --> 11:56.887
[ upbeat folk music ]

11:56.966 --> 11:59.766
<i>♪</i>

11:59.886 --> 12:02.596
[ both panting ]

12:02.722 --> 12:04.142
Man, that is not as easy
in a corset.

12:04.224 --> 12:05.644
[ laughs ]

12:05.725 --> 12:07.185
[ sighs ]
I think I’m getting old.

12:07.268 --> 12:09.278
[ both panting ]

12:09.395 --> 12:11.065
All right,
I’m gonna live dangerously,

12:11.147 --> 12:12.397
dip my toes in the water.

12:12.523 --> 12:15.233
Oh, you’re braver than I am.

12:15.360 --> 12:18.240
I think I might go search
for some more shells.

12:18.321 --> 12:21.611
[ seagulls crying ]

12:21.741 --> 12:23.361
[ sighs ]

12:26.955 --> 12:29.745
[ suspenseful music ]

12:29.874 --> 12:32.754
<i>♪</i>

12:55.275 --> 12:57.655
[ laughs ]

12:57.777 --> 12:59.027
[ sighs ]

13:09.163 --> 13:12.043
<i>♪</i>

13:28.808 --> 13:31.018
<i>‐ DUFF: Are you Malcolm?
</i> <i>‐ YOUNG IAN: Aye.</i>

13:31.144 --> 13:32.974
You must be Captain Bonnet.

13:33.104 --> 13:34.564
Pleased to finally make
your acquaintance.

13:34.647 --> 13:36.647
No, Captain’s not coming.

13:36.733 --> 13:38.563
He sent us to inspect
the goods.

13:38.651 --> 13:40.481
<i>YOUNG IAN:
But that wasn’t
the arrangement.</i>

13:40.570 --> 13:43.370
Arrangement’s changed.

13:43.489 --> 13:45.829
‐ YOUNG IAN: Why?
‐ He had business elsewhere.

13:45.908 --> 13:47.248
<i>You want the whiskey put
</i> <i>on the ship or not?</i>

13:47.327 --> 13:50.497
<i>♪</i>

13:54.167 --> 13:55.047
Where are the barrels?

13:55.168 --> 13:58.218
<i>♪</i>

13:58.338 --> 14:00.218
[ grunts ]

14:00.340 --> 14:01.680
<i>DUFF:
Where are the goods?</i>

14:01.758 --> 14:04.178
Do you know whose time
you’re wasting?

14:04.302 --> 14:05.712
The barrels are in the shed.

14:05.845 --> 14:08.685
<i>♪</i>

14:22.528 --> 14:25.368
[ tense music ]

14:25.448 --> 14:28.118
<i>♪</i>

14:31.120 --> 14:32.280
Aah!

14:32.372 --> 14:35.082
<i>♪</i>

14:40.963 --> 14:43.423
[ Duff moaning ]

14:43.549 --> 14:45.009
What took you so long?

14:45.093 --> 14:47.343
You were doing so well, I didna
think you needed the help.

14:47.428 --> 14:48.928
[ Duff groans ]

14:58.731 --> 15:00.231
Where’s Stephen Bonnet?

15:01.901 --> 15:04.061
‐ Who wants to know?
‐ Where is he?

15:06.197 --> 15:08.997
[ dramatic music ]

15:09.075 --> 15:11.745
<i>♪</i>

15:12.787 --> 15:14.417
JAMIE:
Answer the question.

15:14.497 --> 15:17.247
<i>♪</i>

15:17.375 --> 15:19.085
Where’s Stephen Bonnet?

15:19.168 --> 15:22.088
<i>♪</i>

15:24.298 --> 15:25.718
[ sighs ]

15:27.802 --> 15:30.132
[ suspenseful music ]

15:30.263 --> 15:32.473
They say the sea lives
inside every shell.

15:32.598 --> 15:35.648
<i>♪</i>

15:37.103 --> 15:40.563
Can you hear it...
the sea calling?

15:40.648 --> 15:42.778
What are you doing here?

15:42.900 --> 15:45.440
I was walking down
the thoroughfare in Wilmington

15:45.570 --> 15:47.790
when I saw you from afar.

15:47.864 --> 15:51.744
I thought to myself,
"Doesn’t she look familiar?"

15:51.826 --> 15:54.666
You see,
I never forget a face...

15:54.787 --> 15:56.837
neither yours
nor your lovely daughter’s.

15:56.956 --> 15:57.836
[ grunts ]

15:57.957 --> 16:00.587
<i>♪</i>

16:00.668 --> 16:02.508
She seems to have inherited
your beauty.

16:02.628 --> 16:05.548
<i>♪</i>

16:05.631 --> 16:07.461
How’s my son?

16:07.550 --> 16:08.720
Does he resemble
his handsome father?

16:08.801 --> 16:10.301
You don’t have a son!

16:10.428 --> 16:11.678
<i>You’re misinformed.</i>

16:11.804 --> 16:14.304
Your daughter told me as much
to my face.

16:14.432 --> 16:15.972
I think I found...

16:16.058 --> 16:17.188
Bree, run!

16:17.310 --> 16:18.520
‐ [ Claire gasps ]
‐ No.

16:18.644 --> 16:20.724
[ yelps ]

16:20.813 --> 16:22.393
<i>‐ CLAIRE: Go!
</i>‐ I am not leaving you.

16:22.482 --> 16:24.562
[ pants ]

16:24.650 --> 16:25.690
[ gun cocks ]

16:25.818 --> 16:27.618
‐ Let her go.
‐ Shoot him!

16:27.695 --> 16:28.865
Let her go!

16:28.988 --> 16:30.538
BONNET:
Put that down,

16:30.656 --> 16:31.906
or I’ll cut her throat
on the count of three.

16:33.493 --> 16:36.203
‐ [ Claire panting ]
‐ One, two...

16:36.329 --> 16:37.629
Wait!
Wait.

16:37.705 --> 16:40.795
[ Claire panting ]

16:40.875 --> 16:43.875
I’ll let your mother go...

16:44.003 --> 16:45.373
as long as you come along
with me.

16:47.089 --> 16:50.179
It’s my son and you
I’m wanting.

16:50.301 --> 16:51.381
[ both grunt ]

16:51.511 --> 16:54.011
‐ [ gun clicks ]
‐ [ grunts ]

16:54.138 --> 16:57.018
<i>♪</i>

17:14.534 --> 17:17.364
<i>♪</i>

17:17.453 --> 17:19.373
[ moans softly ]

17:19.497 --> 17:22.337
[ seagulls crying ]

17:22.416 --> 17:25.336
<i>♪</i>

17:25.419 --> 17:26.549
Bree!

17:26.629 --> 17:29.679
<i>♪</i>

17:34.053 --> 17:35.343
Brianna!

17:35.429 --> 17:37.559
<i>♪</i>

17:37.640 --> 17:39.940
[ whimpers ]

17:40.059 --> 17:42.979
<i>♪</i>

18:12.550 --> 18:15.350
[ breathing rapidly ]

18:17.805 --> 18:19.345
Would you like some tea?

18:19.432 --> 18:20.722
Where are we?

18:20.808 --> 18:23.018
<i>You’re safe on my island.</i>

18:24.854 --> 18:26.814
Where the hell is my mother?

18:27.898 --> 18:30.608
I left her on the beach.
I have no quarrel with her.

18:30.693 --> 18:34.533
[ breathing heavily ]

18:34.614 --> 18:37.034
‐ We have a quarrel with you.
<i>‐ Still?</i>

18:39.076 --> 18:40.616
It’s not because I couldn’t
remember your name

18:40.703 --> 18:41.823
<i>in the jail, is it?</i>

18:46.167 --> 18:48.007
Can’t we just let
bygones be bygones?

18:50.796 --> 18:52.716
I have something for you.

18:52.798 --> 18:55.008
[ dark music ]

18:55.134 --> 18:57.134
‐ [ objects clatter gently ]
‐ [ Bonnet grunts softly ]

18:57.261 --> 19:00.181
<i>♪</i>

19:02.767 --> 19:04.647
[ chuckles ]

19:04.727 --> 19:07.817
<i>♪</i>

19:17.907 --> 19:19.287
For our son.

19:20.618 --> 19:22.828
He’s not <i>our</i> son.

19:22.953 --> 19:25.953
His father is my husband,
Roger MacKenzie.

19:26.040 --> 19:27.960
I know you had to tell him
that the boy was his,

19:28.042 --> 19:30.212
but you and I know the truth.

19:30.336 --> 19:32.676
We made him...

19:32.755 --> 19:34.505
and there’s
no denying that.

19:35.883 --> 19:38.173
I want to do right
by you and him...

19:38.302 --> 19:41.262
<i>♪</i>

19:41.347 --> 19:42.687
To be a real father.

19:42.765 --> 19:45.855
<i>♪</i>

20:05.287 --> 20:07.377
I have something
for you, too.

20:07.456 --> 20:10.376
<i>♪</i>

20:25.266 --> 20:26.266
It’s Brianna.

20:26.392 --> 20:27.392
Where is she?

20:27.518 --> 20:28.768
Bonnet has her.

20:28.894 --> 20:30.564
<i>♪</i>

20:30.646 --> 20:31.526
[ horse grunts ]

20:31.605 --> 20:34.485
<i>♪</i>

20:40.197 --> 20:42.907
<i>BONNET:
You look so beautiful
</i> <i>in your gift.</i>

20:44.785 --> 20:46.375
Please come in.

20:49.415 --> 20:51.415
‐ [ door closes ]
‐ Am I supposed to pull out
the chair for you?

20:51.542 --> 20:52.582
[ chuckles ]

20:56.589 --> 20:57.469
Please sit down.

21:00.926 --> 21:02.346
Please.

21:23.115 --> 21:24.955
When we’re at River Run,

21:25.075 --> 21:27.325
we’ll have better servants
to do this for us.

21:27.453 --> 21:30.123
You mean slaves.

21:30.247 --> 21:32.457
Is it the master of the house
who’s supposed to do it?

21:37.421 --> 21:39.211
Should I pass this
with both hands?

21:43.844 --> 21:45.974
You’ll teach me.

21:46.096 --> 21:48.346
I don’t think anyone
can teach you a damn thing.

21:48.474 --> 21:49.894
[ chuckling ]
"A damn thing," huh?

21:49.975 --> 21:51.645
[ chuckles ]

21:51.769 --> 21:53.649
I’m surprised to hear language
like that from a lady.

21:53.729 --> 21:55.489
[ chuckling ]

21:55.564 --> 21:59.154
You think someone lowly like me
can’t better himself?

22:05.157 --> 22:08.997
What I need is something
I can’t buy.

22:09.078 --> 22:10.748
A moral compass?

22:10.830 --> 22:12.960
To make sure our son
knows what to do,

22:13.040 --> 22:14.580
<i>how to get on
in the world.</i>

22:14.667 --> 22:17.087
You can show me how to be
in your world and in his.

22:17.169 --> 22:18.299
Hmm?

22:20.214 --> 22:23.964
Show me what to do, hmm...

22:24.051 --> 22:25.711
how to be a worthy gentleman

22:25.845 --> 22:27.845
and no harm will come to you.

22:27.972 --> 22:29.972
Why do you want to be
a gentleman?

22:31.809 --> 22:33.109
You saw something in me.

22:33.185 --> 22:35.355
[ dramatic music ]

22:35.437 --> 22:37.607
You’re drawn to me.
We’re drawn to each other.

22:37.690 --> 22:41.410
That’s why fate has brought us
together again...

22:41.527 --> 22:42.447
and again...

22:42.528 --> 22:45.238
<i>♪</i>

22:45.364 --> 22:47.364
To be parents to Jeremiah.

22:47.491 --> 22:49.111
<i>♪</i>

22:49.201 --> 22:50.531
[ softly ]
You know his name?

22:50.661 --> 22:52.241
Of course I do.

22:52.371 --> 22:54.531
<i>♪</i>

22:54.665 --> 22:56.335
Let’s eat.

22:56.417 --> 22:59.337
<i>♪</i>

23:13.559 --> 23:16.729
Elbows off the table
in polite society.

23:16.854 --> 23:18.984
<i>♪</i>

23:19.064 --> 23:21.404
And don’t bend down
to your food.

23:21.525 --> 23:23.235
You bring your fork up
to your mouth.

23:23.319 --> 23:26.239
<i>♪</i>

23:42.338 --> 23:45.298
[ suspenseful music ]

23:45.424 --> 23:48.134
<i>♪</i>

23:51.597 --> 23:54.437
[ door closes ]

24:01.607 --> 24:03.107
It’s improper
for a lady and gentleman

24:03.233 --> 24:04.773
to be alone like this.

24:04.860 --> 24:07.730
I can have some of my men
come and join us,
if you’d prefer.

24:07.821 --> 24:09.611
No.

24:09.740 --> 24:10.790
Thank you.

24:18.290 --> 24:19.620
What now, then?

24:21.752 --> 24:23.462
How...

24:23.587 --> 24:25.257
do...

24:25.339 --> 24:27.969
men and women
of our standing...

24:28.092 --> 24:30.592
pass the time?

24:30.678 --> 24:32.018
You could read to me.

24:32.137 --> 24:34.477
That is something
a gentleman would do.

24:37.059 --> 24:40.479
Or if you don’t know how,
then maybe I‐I could
read to you.

24:42.940 --> 24:44.150
Here.

24:47.486 --> 24:48.946
Is that something you do
for our son?

24:49.029 --> 24:50.159
Does he like that?

24:57.329 --> 24:59.919
I love reading...

24:59.999 --> 25:03.299
putting yourself
in other people’s shoes...

25:03.377 --> 25:07.677
living with characters,
learning what drives them.

25:07.756 --> 25:11.676
Usually it’s love, money...

25:11.760 --> 25:13.340
revenge.

25:15.180 --> 25:17.180
Which do you think drives me?

25:18.684 --> 25:21.394
Money.
That’s why I’m here, isn’t it?

25:21.520 --> 25:24.520
Because you want River Run.

25:24.606 --> 25:27.486
It isn’t ladylike to hurt
a man’s pride, surely...

25:27.568 --> 25:30.028
thinking me no better
than a common thief.

25:30.154 --> 25:31.824
Well, it isn’t love, is it?

25:33.198 --> 25:34.368
Prove me wrong.

25:34.491 --> 25:36.861
You don’t hurt
the people you love.

25:38.454 --> 25:42.084
And if it’s revenge,
I have done nothing to you.

25:42.207 --> 25:44.757
There are two sides
to every story.

25:46.837 --> 25:48.257
You don’t know mine.

25:55.554 --> 25:59.394
If I were to tell Jeremiah
my story‐‐our story...

26:00.893 --> 26:04.273
Will he...feel for me?

26:05.481 --> 26:07.851
You can’t make someone
love you.

26:07.941 --> 26:11.231
Well, I’ve heard the expression
"learn to love."

26:11.320 --> 26:12.990
Perhaps you could learn
to love me

26:13.072 --> 26:15.072
for the sake of our son.

26:15.157 --> 26:17.957
I think I could learn
to love you.

26:18.077 --> 26:19.747
[ chuckles ]

26:19.870 --> 26:22.670
[ dramatic music ]

26:22.748 --> 26:25.668
<i>♪</i>

26:33.217 --> 26:36.427
When you came to me
in the jail...

26:36.553 --> 26:39.303
and‐and told me that there’d be
something left of me

26:39.431 --> 26:40.761
on this earth...

26:40.849 --> 26:43.769
<i>♪</i>

26:45.312 --> 26:46.892
I couldn’t forget
how that made me feel.

26:46.980 --> 26:49.890
<i>♪</i>

26:52.444 --> 26:55.574
It wasn’t for revenge or...

26:58.325 --> 26:59.955
For money.

27:00.077 --> 27:02.747
<i>♪</i>

27:04.123 --> 27:05.953
So will you teach me
how to love?

27:06.083 --> 27:08.963
<i>♪</i>

27:13.465 --> 27:16.255
[ shakily ]
I’ll read for you...

27:16.343 --> 27:19.673
like I read to Jeremiah.

27:19.805 --> 27:21.645
[ chuckles ]

27:27.980 --> 27:29.320
[ sighs ]

27:29.439 --> 27:32.319
This book is a good one.

27:32.401 --> 27:33.981
I think you’ll like it.

27:37.781 --> 27:40.741
"The mysterious sea captain
of the <i>Pequod</i>

27:40.826 --> 27:43.166
"was a man named Ahab.

27:43.245 --> 27:44.495
"He stood on two legs‐‐

27:44.580 --> 27:48.000
"one of flesh and bone.

27:48.083 --> 27:52.543
"The other one was‐was made
out of the bones of a whale.

27:52.671 --> 27:55.631
"His leg had been taken
during a voyage

27:55.716 --> 28:00.056
"by another monstrous
white whale known as...

28:00.179 --> 28:01.479
Moby Dick."

28:03.182 --> 28:06.182
This is one
of Jeremiah’s favorites.

28:06.310 --> 28:09.730
So my son likes tales
of the sea.

28:09.855 --> 28:11.355
[ chuckles ]

28:13.692 --> 28:17.772
"Captain Ahab nailed a doubloon
to the mast of his ship

28:17.863 --> 28:20.493
"and swore that there would be
a great prize

28:20.574 --> 28:22.704
"for the first man
to sight the whale.

28:22.784 --> 28:25.074
"He said they would stop
at nothing

28:25.204 --> 28:27.744
"until they found him...

28:27.873 --> 28:29.043
and killed him."

28:29.124 --> 28:30.874
Huh.

28:30.959 --> 28:34.089
<i>♪</i>

28:34.213 --> 28:36.003
Please.
Please keep reading.

28:36.089 --> 28:39.059
<i>♪</i>

28:41.970 --> 28:45.390
BRIANNA:
"The beast was unpredictable,
as was the sea.

28:45.474 --> 28:47.394
<i>"But every day</i>

28:47.476 --> 28:50.356
"they arose thinking
that today would be the day

28:50.437 --> 28:54.277
that they would look
the monster in the eye."

28:54.399 --> 28:56.989
What happens in the end?
Does he get the whale?

28:57.069 --> 28:59.659
Well, you‐you don’t want me
to tell you know, do you?

28:59.738 --> 29:01.578
There’s so much more to come.

29:01.698 --> 29:05.918
You must be tired, and I want
to know how this ends.

29:06.036 --> 29:09.456
I really hope that Ahab
slaughters the whale
and gets his revenge.

29:09.581 --> 29:12.871
Moby Dick capsizes Ahab’s boat,

29:12.960 --> 29:16.510
destroys the ship, and Ahab
is dragged under the sea.

29:18.715 --> 29:20.635
What, the monster prevails?

29:25.097 --> 29:26.807
And Ahab is...

29:26.932 --> 29:29.102
drowned, then?

29:29.226 --> 29:32.726
Well, that depends on which one
you think is the monster...

29:34.898 --> 29:39.658
The man hell‐bent on revenge
or the whale who’s hunted.

29:41.321 --> 29:44.191
The sea is
a treacherous place...

29:44.283 --> 29:46.573
where creatures prey
upon one another.

29:48.787 --> 29:52.297
And the sea herself is...

29:52.374 --> 29:54.004
hungry for souls.

29:55.627 --> 29:56.837
What does that mean?

29:56.962 --> 29:59.212
A nightmare.

29:59.298 --> 30:02.468
<i>♪</i>

30:03.468 --> 30:05.388
The sea, uh...

30:05.470 --> 30:08.130
[ breathes shakily ]

30:08.223 --> 30:09.973
It comes for me.

30:11.601 --> 30:12.971
Darkness closes in.

30:13.061 --> 30:15.931
<i>♪</i>

30:17.649 --> 30:19.109
I cannot move.

30:19.192 --> 30:22.152
<i>♪</i>

30:22.237 --> 30:23.787
No one comes.

30:23.864 --> 30:25.994
<i>♪</i>

30:26.116 --> 30:27.996
No one ever comes.

30:28.076 --> 30:30.996
<i>♪</i>

30:32.914 --> 30:34.204
It’s only a dream.

30:34.333 --> 30:37.833
So you don’t think
any less of me for telling you?

30:37.961 --> 30:39.171
No.

30:40.839 --> 30:42.719
I could never think
any less of you.

30:42.841 --> 30:45.761
<i>♪</i>

30:47.721 --> 30:49.681
Does Jeremiah get scared,

30:49.765 --> 30:51.805
have nightmares and the like?

30:53.101 --> 30:54.561
Sometimes.

30:56.772 --> 30:58.182
He’s only a little boy.

31:00.275 --> 31:02.025
He needs his mother.

31:02.152 --> 31:03.272
Oh, I never had a mother...

31:03.362 --> 31:06.362
<i>♪</i>

31:06.448 --> 31:08.368
Or a father...

31:08.492 --> 31:09.952
or a‐‐

31:10.035 --> 31:11.745
I was an orphan.

31:11.870 --> 31:14.700
<i>♪</i>

31:22.381 --> 31:23.711
What do you do
to comfort him?

31:26.051 --> 31:28.051
How could I...

31:28.178 --> 31:29.678
comfort him?

31:31.431 --> 31:33.051
Please...

31:34.559 --> 31:36.319
Please tell me.

31:36.395 --> 31:39.275
<i>♪</i>

31:40.440 --> 31:42.060
I would go to him...

31:42.150 --> 31:44.400
<i>♪</i>

31:44.486 --> 31:47.866
Take him in my arms...

31:47.948 --> 31:50.408
and I would hold him there
until he feels safe.

31:50.492 --> 31:53.072
<i>♪</i>

31:53.161 --> 31:54.781
[ gasps ]

31:56.498 --> 31:57.338
Will you show me?

31:57.416 --> 32:00.586
<i>♪</i>

32:01.795 --> 32:03.835
A lady would say
"good night" now,

32:03.922 --> 32:07.092
and she would go to her bed...

32:08.510 --> 32:10.220
[ sniffles ]

32:10.303 --> 32:11.553
Alone.

32:11.638 --> 32:14.478
[ breathes deeply ]

32:14.599 --> 32:17.609
<i>♪</i>

32:20.272 --> 32:23.272
Then I look forward
to bidding you good morning.

32:23.400 --> 32:26.320
<i>♪</i>

32:26.445 --> 32:27.905
Me too.

32:27.988 --> 32:30.908
<i>♪</i>

32:43.545 --> 32:46.175
‐ [ breathing heavily ]
‐ [ lock clicks ]

32:48.675 --> 32:51.635
[ dishes clattering gently ]

33:13.825 --> 33:15.825
Good morning, my lady.

33:20.165 --> 33:21.625
Breakfast is served.

33:31.676 --> 33:32.886
[ clears throat ]

33:34.554 --> 33:36.764
[ Bonnet grunts softly ]
Tea?

33:46.274 --> 33:48.194
So would we live here?

33:56.409 --> 33:58.579
We could live anywhere
you’d like,

33:58.703 --> 34:00.833
a place in town,
if it pleases you.

34:06.002 --> 34:09.582
I was thinking I should go
and fetch Jeremiah.

34:09.714 --> 34:12.174
I can’t be away from him
for too long.

34:12.259 --> 34:14.059
Mm.
I’ll come with you.

34:14.177 --> 34:17.847
Perhaps it would be better
if I tell him

34:17.931 --> 34:20.391
that you’re going to be
in his life.

34:20.517 --> 34:23.267
We don’t want to upset him.

34:23.395 --> 34:24.895
He is only young.

34:27.357 --> 34:29.527
We don’t how my family are
going to react.

34:29.609 --> 34:32.619
My father and Roger are...

34:32.737 --> 34:36.037
well, they’re‐they’re not
like you.

34:36.116 --> 34:38.956
<i>It would be more prudent
</i> <i>if I were to go.</i>

34:39.077 --> 34:42.747
Then I’ll come back to you.

34:42.831 --> 34:46.701
Fate will bring me
back to you...

34:46.793 --> 34:49.213
like it has before.

34:49.296 --> 34:50.716
Is that what you want?

34:50.797 --> 34:54.307
Well, it’s what we both want,
isn’t it?

34:57.762 --> 35:00.092
When would you go?

35:00.181 --> 35:03.221
Should we not spend more time
together here first to bond?

35:03.310 --> 35:05.530
I miss Jemmy so much,

35:05.604 --> 35:09.024
and I know
that you wanted to meet him.

35:09.107 --> 35:12.817
The sooner I can leave...

35:12.944 --> 35:14.824
the sooner I will return
to you.

35:24.581 --> 35:26.621
Yes.

35:26.750 --> 35:28.210
[ chuckles ]

35:28.293 --> 35:31.123
[ dramatic music ]

35:31.254 --> 35:33.714
<i>♪</i>

35:33.798 --> 35:38.558
And while you’re gone,
I’ll go to Wilmington
and find us a place...

35:38.637 --> 35:40.597
with a parlor
and a bedchamber for us

35:40.680 --> 35:41.970
and for our son.

35:44.100 --> 35:46.970
And we’ll seal our promise
to one another with a kiss.

35:47.062 --> 35:48.642
<i>♪</i>

35:48.772 --> 35:50.692
[ chuckles ]

35:50.815 --> 35:53.865
<i>♪</i>

36:10.669 --> 36:12.179
[ chuckles ]

36:17.509 --> 36:21.229
If there’s one thing
I don’t need to be taught...

36:21.346 --> 36:23.056
it’s what a kiss is.

36:23.181 --> 36:25.471
<i>♪</i>

36:25.558 --> 36:28.398
‐ [ chuckles nervously ]
That was just our first time‐‐
‐ Don’t.

36:28.520 --> 36:29.900
St‐Stephen, we should‐we should
try again‐‐

36:30.021 --> 36:31.061
I’m not good enough
for you, eh?

36:31.189 --> 36:32.699
No, no.
That is not‐‐

36:32.774 --> 36:35.354
I’ll give you a reason
to despise me.

36:35.443 --> 36:39.283
I‐I‐I hoped‐I hoped you were
being truthful.

36:39.364 --> 36:40.284
I was.
I...

36:40.365 --> 36:43.785
I let my feelings
cloud my judgment.

36:43.868 --> 36:47.538
And the last time I did that,
I was a young workman,

36:47.622 --> 36:50.162
and I was fooled into thinking
the other men liked me.

36:50.250 --> 36:53.010
And they got me drunk,
and they left me for dead

36:53.086 --> 36:55.546
in the foundations of a cellar
I’d helped them dig.

36:55.672 --> 37:00.052
I don’t need you to get Jemmy.

37:00.135 --> 37:02.975
<i>♪</i>

37:03.054 --> 37:04.884
[ breathing heavily ]

37:05.014 --> 37:06.724
[ whispers ]
I’ll show you
what you’re missing.

37:06.808 --> 37:09.898
<i>♪</i>

37:16.484 --> 37:17.614
[ gasps ]

37:17.736 --> 37:19.736
[ moans softly ]

37:19.863 --> 37:22.693
[ both breathing heavily ]

37:22.782 --> 37:24.742
[ moans ]

37:24.826 --> 37:27.416
<i>♪</i>

37:27.537 --> 37:29.957
[ moans ]

37:30.081 --> 37:33.371
[ both grunting ]

37:33.460 --> 37:36.300
[ both moaning ]

37:37.964 --> 37:39.594
[ Bonnet grunting ]

37:40.925 --> 37:42.715
[ moans ]

37:42.802 --> 37:45.722
[ grunting ]

37:45.805 --> 37:48.845
[ both moaning ]

37:48.933 --> 37:51.473
‐ [ Bonnet groaning ]
‐ [ breathing heavily ]

37:54.481 --> 37:56.981
[ panting ]

37:57.108 --> 38:00.068
[ Bonnet moaning ]

38:00.153 --> 38:03.613
[ both breathing heavily ]

38:03.698 --> 38:07.288
For a few pennies more,
you could watch me and her.

38:07.410 --> 38:09.820
<i>♪</i>

38:09.954 --> 38:12.994
That one won’t be
enjoying herself today.

38:13.124 --> 38:15.124
<i>EPPIE:
Then I’ll collect my money.</i>

38:16.461 --> 38:19.711
But send for me again
when it suits you.

38:19.798 --> 38:21.098
I’ll fetch your coin.

38:23.426 --> 38:26.056
But don’t let her
out of your sight.

38:27.847 --> 38:29.727
[ door closes ]

38:29.808 --> 38:31.108
Do you know where we are?

38:31.184 --> 38:34.644
This place?
Ocracoke.

38:36.314 --> 38:38.234
Do you know Mr. Bonnet well?

38:38.316 --> 38:39.486
Yes.

38:41.152 --> 38:43.272
He sends for me
when the fancy takes him,

38:43.363 --> 38:45.323
or he brings me out
on a boat with him.

38:45.406 --> 38:49.496
He’s fond of breakfast in bed,
if you take my meaning.

38:49.577 --> 38:52.787
<i>But I’ve never known him
to have two girls together</i>

38:52.872 --> 38:57.082
or to be wanting someone watch
while he’s at his pleasure.

38:57.168 --> 38:58.508
Was it to your liking?

38:58.586 --> 39:00.376
You don’t understand.

39:00.505 --> 39:02.385
He’s holding me here
against my will.

39:02.507 --> 39:06.017
Well, whoever you are,
he takes what he wants

39:06.094 --> 39:09.844
and you better not cross him.

39:09.973 --> 39:12.973
‐ What’s your name?
‐ They call me Eppie.

39:13.059 --> 39:15.519
Eppie, I have to get away
from here.

39:15.645 --> 39:17.685
Chances are he’ll tire of you
in a few days.

39:17.814 --> 39:20.854
No, you don’t‐
that’s not‐that’s not
what he wants from me.

39:20.984 --> 39:24.234
<i>‐ EPPIE: Is it money?
</i> ‐ No, I...

39:24.362 --> 39:25.692
He means to ransom you?

39:25.822 --> 39:27.032
<i>I’ve never known scruples</i>

39:27.156 --> 39:28.326
<i>to interfere
with the man’s appetite.</i>

39:28.408 --> 39:29.458
Here.

39:29.534 --> 39:32.874
If I give you this,
will you help me?

39:32.954 --> 39:34.704
Help you do what?

39:34.831 --> 39:36.201
Get word to my husband.

39:36.332 --> 39:39.542
His name is Roger MacKenzie,
and he’s in Wilmington,

39:39.669 --> 39:41.679
as is my father, James Fraser.

39:41.754 --> 39:43.334
You need to tell them
where I am.

39:43.423 --> 39:46.713
Rich, your family, then,
are they?

39:46.801 --> 39:48.341
Very.

39:51.055 --> 39:53.145
I’d like to help you,

39:53.224 --> 39:55.934
but Bonnet is a fair man

39:56.060 --> 39:59.480
as long as your interests run
with his.

39:59.564 --> 40:01.484
If it doesn’t,
there won’t be no warning.

40:01.566 --> 40:03.356
‐ Please‐‐
‐ One moment, whiskey and song,

40:03.443 --> 40:06.363
the next,
you’re breathing blood...

40:06.446 --> 40:08.406
if you’re still breathing
at all.

40:08.531 --> 40:09.611
[ sighs ]

40:09.741 --> 40:12.361
Mind your tongue,
and all will be well.

40:12.452 --> 40:14.452
‐ I am begging you,
woman to woman‐‐
‐ [ door opens ]

40:14.579 --> 40:17.749
[ coins rattle ]

40:17.832 --> 40:20.622
[ somber music ]

40:20.752 --> 40:23.622
<i>♪</i>

40:28.426 --> 40:29.556
Fuck.

40:31.012 --> 40:32.052
[ sniffles ]

40:32.138 --> 40:35.858
[ breathing shakily ]

40:35.934 --> 40:38.104
<i>♪</i>

40:38.227 --> 40:41.487
‐ ROGER: Mr. Wylie!
‐ [ grunts, whimpering ]

40:41.606 --> 40:42.776
Yet.

40:42.899 --> 40:44.409
What is the meaning of this?

40:44.484 --> 40:46.114
Why are you accosting me
in the street?

40:46.194 --> 40:48.774
Tell us where Bonnet is.

40:48.863 --> 40:50.733
<i>JAMIE:
You said he’d come to us,
</i> <i>but he didn’t.</i>

40:50.823 --> 40:54.113
Did you give us up?
Did you tell him it was me?

40:54.202 --> 40:57.242
No, I swear.
I don’t know where he is.

40:57.330 --> 40:59.460
He keeps his goods
at my landing,

40:59.540 --> 41:01.290
and all I did was arrange
for him to meet you there.

41:01.376 --> 41:03.216
‐ He has my wife!
‐ [ Wylie yelps ]

41:03.294 --> 41:05.004
Where’s his ship?
Where does he make berth?

41:05.129 --> 41:07.759
I don’t know.
If I did, I’d tell you.

41:07.840 --> 41:09.210
[ chokes ]

41:09.300 --> 41:11.050
He’s made my life a misery,

41:11.135 --> 41:12.475
threatening me with blackmail

41:12.595 --> 41:14.635
over business
he draws profit from.

41:14.764 --> 41:16.644
[ whimpers ] Please.

41:16.724 --> 41:18.144
[ gasps ]

41:21.479 --> 41:22.739
[ whimpers ]

41:22.814 --> 41:25.314
There’s a brothel he frequents,
Mistress Sylvie’s.

41:25.400 --> 41:27.660
He and I have had
meetings there in the past.

41:27.777 --> 41:31.037
I’m sure you will find
someone there who knows Bonnet.

41:31.155 --> 41:33.655
[ stuttering ]
He is a creature of habit.

41:33.783 --> 41:35.323
[ panting ]

41:35.410 --> 41:37.670
And make yourself scarce,
Mr. Wylie.

41:37.787 --> 41:39.127
Without a shadow of a doubt.

41:39.205 --> 41:41.915
[ dramatic music ]

41:42.000 --> 41:43.380
[ gasps ]

41:43.501 --> 41:46.331
<i>♪</i>

41:48.006 --> 41:49.716
You two stay in the tavern

41:49.841 --> 41:52.381
in case Bonnet or his men come
looking for us.

41:52.510 --> 41:54.590
Dinna ken what he might do.

41:54.679 --> 41:57.059
Claire and I will pay
Mistress Sylvie a visit.

41:57.181 --> 42:00.141
<i>♪</i>

42:00.226 --> 42:03.066
[ birds chirping ]

42:03.187 --> 42:06.277
<i>♪</i>

42:15.742 --> 42:18.112
Will ye have Mary fetch
some of her wee cakes, Ulysses?

42:18.202 --> 42:19.372
Of course, sir.

42:19.454 --> 42:21.534
There’s no need, Ulysses.

42:21.622 --> 42:24.752
This is business, not pleasure.
We can eat afterwards.

42:24.876 --> 42:26.506
Very good, Mistress.

42:28.212 --> 42:30.672
‐ There.
‐ [ scoffs ] I’m not invalid.

42:30.757 --> 42:35.057
<i>DUNCAN:
But you’ve been suffering
wi’ yer headaches of late.</i>

42:35.178 --> 42:38.638
I have been looking forward
to this.

42:38.723 --> 42:42.303
You have my blessing to do
as you wish, my dear.

42:42.393 --> 42:43.643
[ Ulysses clears throat ]

42:43.728 --> 42:46.648
Mr. Forbes, Mistress.

42:46.731 --> 42:48.641
I’ll leave you to it.

42:53.029 --> 42:55.119
[ clears throat ]

42:55.239 --> 42:57.039
<i>ULYSSES:
I’ll see you’re not disturbed.</i>

42:57.116 --> 42:58.406
[ door closes ]

42:58.493 --> 43:01.033
A pleasure as always,
Mistress Innes.

43:01.120 --> 43:02.660
[ grunts ]

43:02.747 --> 43:04.207
What can I do for you?

43:04.290 --> 43:08.000
My nephew, Jamie, visited us
not so long ago

43:08.086 --> 43:10.836
with happy news from the Ridge.

43:10.922 --> 43:14.042
My great nephew, Ian,
has returned from the Mohawk.

43:14.133 --> 43:16.633
Oh, really?
How interesting.

43:16.761 --> 43:19.091
<i>And Marsali’s had
another bairn,</i>

43:19.222 --> 43:20.722
a wee girl.

43:20.807 --> 43:22.227
Oh, yeah, that’s lovely.

43:22.308 --> 43:25.018
So I was thinking...

43:25.103 --> 43:27.433
we’re very comfortable,
Mr. Innes and I,

43:27.522 --> 43:29.272
<i>and we will be
for the rest of our days.</i>

43:29.398 --> 43:31.778
We dinna want for much.

43:31.901 --> 43:34.521
[ chuckles ]
We canna take it with us
when we...

43:34.612 --> 43:37.692
You can’t take what with you?

43:37.782 --> 43:41.572
Our earthly belongings,
Mr. Forbes.

43:41.661 --> 43:44.831
I want you to help me bestow
some gifts

43:44.956 --> 43:46.996
upon my family.

43:47.125 --> 43:49.795
Gifts?
What kind of gifts?

43:51.170 --> 43:52.710
My fortune.

43:52.797 --> 43:55.597
[ unsettling music ]

43:55.675 --> 43:58.715
<i>♪</i>

43:58.803 --> 44:01.723
[ indistinct chatter ]

44:01.806 --> 44:04.606
[ wagon clattering ]

44:07.436 --> 44:10.236
‐ [ indistinct chatter ]
‐ [ door opens ]

44:10.314 --> 44:13.774
[ solemn violin music playing ]

44:13.860 --> 44:16.240
[ door closes ]

44:16.320 --> 44:18.820
Can I help you?

44:18.948 --> 44:20.408
Good afternoon.

44:20.491 --> 44:23.741
Unusual to have
husband and wife visit,

44:23.828 --> 44:25.498
but not unheard of.

44:25.580 --> 44:28.300
Mabel wouldn’t mind
being partial to women.

44:28.374 --> 44:31.914
No, we’re not here for that.

44:32.003 --> 44:35.253
We would like to speak
to your ladies, urgently.

44:35.339 --> 44:38.219
That’ll be 10 shillings
for the inconvenience.

44:38.342 --> 44:40.462
And what price would you put
on a girl’s life?

44:40.553 --> 44:42.013
Are you threatening me?

44:42.138 --> 44:43.888
No.

44:46.893 --> 44:48.853
We’re looking for someone,

44:48.936 --> 44:52.896
and we have reason to believe
that you or some of your ladies

44:53.024 --> 44:54.654
might know where he is.

44:54.734 --> 44:57.864
We’re looking for a man named
Stephen Bonnet.

44:57.945 --> 44:59.695
[ woman clears throat ]

45:01.365 --> 45:04.245
[ dramatic music ]

45:04.368 --> 45:07.458
<i>♪</i>

45:07.538 --> 45:11.708
You’ll find paper and writing
implements on the table.

45:13.336 --> 45:15.126
Wonderful.

45:15.213 --> 45:16.833
Now...

45:16.923 --> 45:20.713
Marsali and Fergus, I’d like
to give them 100 pounds.

45:23.721 --> 45:24.931
Generous.

45:25.056 --> 45:27.226
And you’re, uh, certain

45:27.350 --> 45:29.520
that Mr. Innes
is amenable to this?

45:29.602 --> 45:31.522
He is indeed amenable.

45:31.604 --> 45:34.734
Oh, you’re fortunate to have
found such a good match.

45:34.857 --> 45:37.197
<i>JOCASTA:
</i> <i>And 50 pounds
for their son, Germain,</i>

45:37.276 --> 45:38.816
<i>and of course for Joanie.</i>

45:38.903 --> 45:40.573
20 for the wee one

45:40.696 --> 45:44.406
and perhaps 20 more for luck.

45:44.492 --> 45:46.572
Are you recording this?

45:46.702 --> 45:47.992
Of course.

45:49.747 --> 45:51.377
Every word.

45:51.457 --> 45:53.007
<i>Do stop me
if I go too quickly.</i>

45:53.084 --> 45:54.544
Oh, not at all.

45:54.627 --> 45:56.547
Young Ian, bless him,

45:56.629 --> 45:59.509
something to get him
on his feet.

45:59.590 --> 46:03.090
100‐‐no.
200 pounds.

46:03.177 --> 46:05.347
[ chuckles ]

46:05.429 --> 46:07.899
Well, that is
astonishingly kind.

46:07.974 --> 46:09.434
You hardly know the lad.

46:09.558 --> 46:11.568
And he’s been living
with the Indians.

46:11.644 --> 46:15.434
Nevertheless, he is kin.

46:15.564 --> 46:18.024
Was it not enough
to bequeath your property

46:18.109 --> 46:19.659
to young Jeremiah MacKenzie?

46:19.777 --> 46:21.777
<i>You’re diminishing
from his inheritance.</i>

46:21.862 --> 46:23.942
’Tis better to give
than to receive.

46:26.075 --> 46:28.455
Brianna and Roger...

46:28.577 --> 46:31.287
I’m hoping to give them
a sizable sum.

46:31.414 --> 46:34.504
Perhaps 1,000 pounds.

46:34.625 --> 46:37.465
[ uneasy music ]

46:37.545 --> 46:39.425
[ breathes shakily ]
Well...

46:39.505 --> 46:41.675
[ taps desk ]
There we are.

46:41.799 --> 46:44.309
<i>♪</i>

46:44.385 --> 46:48.345
Miss Brianna and her husband

46:48.472 --> 46:50.802
will be
quite comfortable as well.

46:50.891 --> 46:53.351
Gerald...

46:53.477 --> 46:56.647
I had hoped it would be you
she chose,

46:56.731 --> 47:00.601
<i>but ’tis all water
under the bridge by now.</i>

47:00.693 --> 47:02.313
Aye.

47:02.403 --> 47:05.733
Ooh, we mustn’t forget
young Lizzie.

47:05.823 --> 47:07.153
The servant?

47:07.283 --> 47:09.283
<i>She’s a poor sweet thin.</i>

47:09.368 --> 47:11.168
25 pounds?

47:11.245 --> 47:13.995
‐ No.
‐ No?

47:14.081 --> 47:16.791
Whatever is the matter,
Mr. Forbes?

47:16.876 --> 47:19.296
You can’t give away
my money.

47:19.378 --> 47:21.088
Your money?

47:21.172 --> 47:23.132
You’ve left me no choice.

47:23.215 --> 47:25.385
[ muffled screaming ]

47:25.509 --> 47:27.559
You’ve robbed me
of my dignity.

47:27.678 --> 47:30.558
I would have been a good
husband to you or Brianna!

47:30.681 --> 47:32.681
[ bell dings ]

47:32.767 --> 47:35.977
You won’t rob me
of my share in your fortune!

47:37.688 --> 47:40.028
‐ [ grunting ]
‐ [ Jocasta coughs ]

47:40.107 --> 47:41.527
[ gasps ]

47:41.650 --> 47:42.600
‐ [ Ulysses grunts ]
‐ [ Forbes groans ]

47:42.693 --> 47:44.523
[ both grunting ]

47:44.612 --> 47:46.022
‐ [ Forbes gurgles ]
‐ [ bone snaps ]

47:46.113 --> 47:49.033
[ suspenseful music ]

47:49.158 --> 47:50.868
ULYSSES:
Mistress!

47:50.993 --> 47:52.913
<i>♪</i>

47:53.037 --> 47:54.837
<i>Mistress.</i>

47:56.082 --> 47:57.542
Mistress.

47:57.625 --> 47:59.415
[ soft music ]

47:59.543 --> 48:01.043
<i>♪</i>

48:01.128 --> 48:03.588
Jocasta.

48:03.714 --> 48:05.044
[ gasps softly ]

48:05.132 --> 48:08.012
<i>♪</i>

48:16.394 --> 48:18.064
Never heard of him.

48:24.819 --> 48:27.529
Your hip...anisomelia.

48:27.613 --> 48:29.233
What did you call me?

48:29.365 --> 48:31.195
I didn’t call you anything.

48:31.283 --> 48:33.783
I merely identified what’s
causing the pain in your hip

48:33.911 --> 48:35.741
and your back and the pain

48:35.830 --> 48:38.090
that shoots down your leg
from time to time.

48:38.165 --> 48:39.705
How did‐‐

48:41.627 --> 48:42.757
Are you a conjure woman?

48:42.837 --> 48:44.007
No.

48:46.090 --> 48:47.510
I’m a healer,

48:47.591 --> 48:50.631
and I can tell that you’re
in a great deal of pain.

48:50.761 --> 48:51.921
Let me help you.

48:52.054 --> 48:53.634
Please.

48:53.764 --> 48:56.644
[ violin music playing softly ]

48:56.767 --> 48:59.647
♪

48:59.770 --> 49:02.890
Turn around.
Give me your gown.

49:05.985 --> 49:08.905
Here, hold on
to the chair.

49:11.282 --> 49:12.742
Ah.

49:15.453 --> 49:18.123
Did you know
that your legs are uneven?

49:18.247 --> 49:19.837
Your left leg‐‐

49:19.957 --> 49:22.377
well, it’s longer
than your right.

49:22.460 --> 49:26.090
And lift your right heel
as I adjust it.

49:26.172 --> 49:29.252
♪

49:29.341 --> 49:30.381
<i>CLAIRE:
Lift up.</i>

49:30.468 --> 49:33.138
♪

49:33.220 --> 49:34.970
<i>There.</i>

49:35.055 --> 49:38.105
♪

49:38.184 --> 49:40.264
Any half‐decent cobbler

49:40.352 --> 49:42.772
should be able to make you
a lift about this thickness.

49:42.855 --> 49:44.985
It should greatly reduce
your pain.

49:45.107 --> 49:47.657
Perhaps even in time,
it will completely disappear.

49:49.278 --> 49:50.868
I’m not so popular

49:50.988 --> 49:54.748
as to have spare money going
for fancy shoes.

49:54.825 --> 49:57.825
I’ll be happy to make
a contribution.

49:57.912 --> 49:58.912
Why?

49:58.996 --> 50:00.916
Because when someone
is in need

50:00.998 --> 50:04.048
and you can help,
then you help.

50:04.168 --> 50:05.838
Please...

50:05.961 --> 50:08.171
Stephen Bonnet took
my daughter.

50:08.255 --> 50:11.385
She has a husband
and a small child,

50:11.509 --> 50:13.139
and I need to bring her home.

50:13.219 --> 50:15.139
[ dramatic music ]

50:15.221 --> 50:17.881
[ whispering ]
If he ever learned it was me,
he’d slit my throat.

50:18.015 --> 50:19.895
[ whispering ]
He will never find out.

50:20.017 --> 50:22.897
<i>♪</i>

50:24.688 --> 50:25.898
You’ll need a boat.

50:26.023 --> 50:28.733
<i>♪</i>

50:28.859 --> 50:30.739
[ door opens ]

50:30.861 --> 50:32.191
I found a boat
from a fisherman.

50:32.279 --> 50:33.789
Very good.
Let’s go.

50:33.864 --> 50:35.364
What did you pay him with?

50:35.491 --> 50:36.861
I didna need money, Auntie.

50:36.992 --> 50:39.202
He gladly took Mr. Malcolm’s
new clothes in return.

50:39.286 --> 50:40.246
Heh.

50:41.830 --> 50:44.700
Come and greet Captain Howard,
sweetheart.

50:44.833 --> 50:46.873
Please, sir,
I’m being held against my will.

50:46.961 --> 50:50.251
My husband and my‐‐
[ grunting ]

50:50.381 --> 50:51.881
Of course you are.

50:51.966 --> 50:52.966
I wouldn’t be here
to make a purchase

50:53.050 --> 50:54.710
if you were here voluntarily.

50:57.054 --> 50:58.384
Oh.

50:58.514 --> 51:01.224
<i>♪</i>

51:01.350 --> 51:03.400
[ sniffs ]

51:03.519 --> 51:06.899
Very lovely indeed.

51:08.399 --> 51:11.779
But the red hair‐‐
I do prefer a flaxen mane.

51:11.902 --> 51:14.612
[ moaning creepily ]

51:14.738 --> 51:16.578
<i>♪</i>

51:16.699 --> 51:19.749
‐ [ Howard chuckles ]
‐ [ Brianna grunts ]

51:19.827 --> 51:21.877
<i>HOWARD:
She’s very fine.</i>

51:21.954 --> 51:25.244
She’s in good health.

51:25.374 --> 51:27.414
The teeth...ah.

51:27.543 --> 51:30.123
Ah.

51:30.254 --> 51:31.634
The teeth.

51:31.755 --> 51:34.715
<i>♪</i>

51:34.800 --> 51:36.960
[ Brianna grunts ]

51:37.094 --> 51:39.424
‐ Aha. Ha.
‐ [ whimpers ]

51:39.513 --> 51:41.473
Ah, very nice.

51:41.599 --> 51:43.019
HOWARD:
Has she‐‐

51:43.100 --> 51:44.640
HOWARD: Ah!

51:44.768 --> 51:46.478
[ coughs, gasping ]

51:46.604 --> 51:48.184
[ chuckles ]

51:48.272 --> 51:49.642
Wild bitch.

51:49.773 --> 51:53.113
Captain, she’s not yours yet,
is she?

51:53.235 --> 51:54.365
[ gasps ]

51:54.445 --> 51:56.945
Mine or not...

51:57.031 --> 52:00.361
someone should teach her
some manners.

52:00.451 --> 52:04.451
I admit, I don’t often shy away
from a challenge...

52:05.998 --> 52:08.508
Breaking a wild mare.

52:08.626 --> 52:10.006
Six pounds.

52:10.127 --> 52:13.007
<i>♪</i>

52:22.473 --> 52:24.053
We’re old friends.

52:26.477 --> 52:27.647
You can take her for six.

52:27.770 --> 52:29.900
<i>She’s nothing but property.</i>

52:30.898 --> 52:32.278
She’s not worth more than that.

52:33.692 --> 52:35.982
‐ We’re agreed, then?
‐ Yes.

52:36.070 --> 52:37.950
She’s yours as soon
as I see the money.

52:38.030 --> 52:41.790
[ chuckles ]
Follow me to the boat.

52:41.867 --> 52:43.617
Manny holds the purse.

52:43.702 --> 52:45.492
Very well.

52:45.621 --> 52:46.871
[ Howard chuckles ]

52:46.997 --> 52:48.497
First,
let’s have another drink.

52:48.624 --> 52:50.914
<i>♪</i>

52:51.001 --> 52:53.871
For you, sweetheart, brandy.

52:54.004 --> 52:55.334
You’ve earned it.

52:55.422 --> 52:57.292
Please.

52:57.383 --> 53:01.553
Please, don’t do this.
Please, I am begging you.

53:01.679 --> 53:03.479
I can’t be parted from Jemmy.

53:03.555 --> 53:05.055
Please don’t do this.

53:05.182 --> 53:07.682
<i>♪</i>

53:07.810 --> 53:10.690
Don’t worry.
I’ll take care of him.

53:10.771 --> 53:13.851
<i>♪</i>

53:15.984 --> 53:18.864
[ bell ringing
in the distance ]

53:20.614 --> 53:22.574
[ Brianna and Bonnet grunting ]

53:22.700 --> 53:23.960
[ laughs ]

53:24.034 --> 53:26.364
[ breathing heavily ]

53:26.453 --> 53:28.703
Manny...

53:28.831 --> 53:30.541
my purse.

53:30.666 --> 53:33.546
<i>♪</i>

53:37.631 --> 53:39.381
[ gunshot ]

53:39.466 --> 53:40.506
CLAIRE:
Bree!

53:40.592 --> 53:43.512
<i>♪</i>

53:43.595 --> 53:45.055
Manny!

53:46.724 --> 53:47.644
Brianna!

53:47.725 --> 53:50.565
<i>♪</i>

53:52.229 --> 53:54.399
‐ [ breathing heavily ]
‐ You’re safe.

53:54.523 --> 53:55.393
[ gun cocks ]

53:55.482 --> 53:57.732
<i>♪</i>

53:57.818 --> 53:59.698
We’ll take our leave.

53:59.778 --> 54:01.078
To the boat, lad.

54:01.155 --> 54:04.075
<i>♪</i>

54:10.164 --> 54:12.954
[ Roger groaning loudly ]

54:13.083 --> 54:14.663
HOWARD:
Come on.

54:14.752 --> 54:17.622
<i>♪</i>

54:31.101 --> 54:34.141
[ exhaling deeply ]

54:34.271 --> 54:37.101
<i>♪</i>

54:43.781 --> 54:45.741
Do you think his men
will come for him?

54:45.824 --> 54:47.864
Not if they have any sense.

54:47.951 --> 54:49.361
They’ll be rid of him
soon enough.

54:49.453 --> 54:51.953
They’ll have a ship
and their freedom.

54:52.080 --> 54:54.240
And we saved them the bother
of a mutiny.

55:07.137 --> 55:09.097
You can have a drop...
for your soul.

55:10.474 --> 55:13.314
[ moans, grunting ]

55:16.730 --> 55:18.390
Know that whatever happens,

55:18.482 --> 55:20.482
the last face
you’ll see on this earth

55:20.609 --> 55:21.739
willna be that of a friend.

55:21.819 --> 55:24.779
[ breathing heavily ]

55:24.863 --> 55:27.693
[ grunting ]

55:27.825 --> 55:29.575
I want to take him
to Wilmington.

55:29.660 --> 55:33.000
I want him to be judged
according to the law.

55:34.706 --> 55:37.046
But can you trust them?

55:37.167 --> 55:40.337
His dealings have bought a lot
of influence in Wilmington.

55:40.462 --> 55:41.332
Tryon.

55:43.841 --> 55:45.341
This bastard
may have influence

55:45.425 --> 55:47.135
with businessmen
and landowners,

55:47.219 --> 55:50.099
but surely Governor Tryon
outdoes them all...

55:50.180 --> 55:51.800
even from New York.

55:51.890 --> 55:53.350
<i>JAMIE:
</i> <i>Aye.</i>

55:53.433 --> 55:56.643
Tryon still owes us
for his mistake at Alamance.

55:56.728 --> 55:58.648
He’ll see him condemned.

55:58.730 --> 56:00.190
<i>That I’m sure of.</i>

56:02.484 --> 56:05.364
<i>♪</i>

56:07.698 --> 56:10.538
[ geese honking ]

56:10.617 --> 56:13.077
<i>♪</i>

56:13.203 --> 56:15.493
Stephen Bonnet,

56:15.581 --> 56:18.621
known pirate and smuggler,
was tried this morning

56:18.709 --> 56:21.169
<i>before the Wilmington
Committee of Safety.</i>

56:21.253 --> 56:23.213
And upon testimony
of his crimes

56:23.338 --> 56:25.888
having been presented
by a number of persons,

56:25.966 --> 56:27.426
was convicted of them

56:27.551 --> 56:29.711
and sentenced to death
by drowning.

56:29.845 --> 56:32.725
<i>♪</i>

56:38.020 --> 56:40.400
[ Bonnet breathing heavily ]

56:40.522 --> 56:42.482
<i>♪</i>

56:42.566 --> 56:45.816
[ screaming ]

56:45.903 --> 56:49.073
<i>♪</i>

56:56.580 --> 56:59.420
[ grunting ]

56:59.541 --> 57:02.411
<i>♪</i>

57:07.591 --> 57:10.421
[ exhaling sharply ]

57:10.552 --> 57:13.432
<i>♪</i>

57:14.765 --> 57:17.605
[ breathing heavily ]

57:17.684 --> 57:20.604
<i>♪</i>

57:25.776 --> 57:28.656
[ grunts, spits ]

57:28.779 --> 57:31.829
[ geese honking ]

57:31.949 --> 57:34.619
[ groans loudly,
breathing heavily ]

57:34.701 --> 57:37.411
<i>♪</i>

57:43.043 --> 57:45.793
[ breathing slows ]

57:45.921 --> 57:48.791
<i>♪</i>

57:50.092 --> 57:52.632
[ gunshot ]

58:06.316 --> 58:09.486
[ reeds rustling ]

58:09.611 --> 58:12.481
<i>♪</i>

58:14.032 --> 58:15.152
<i>ROGER:
Brianna?</i>

58:17.119 --> 58:19.169
Was that mercy?

58:20.580 --> 58:22.910
Or was it
to make sure he’s dead?

58:23.000 --> 58:25.670
<i>♪</i>

59:51.088 --> 59:52.428
[ wind blows,
seagull cries ]
